ort from native-stock elites; municipal populists found support among stock immigrant groups and segments of the working class; and progressive candidates won the backing of coalitions made up of traditional reform and municipal populist voters. The success of these reform efforts, Finegold shows, depended on the different ways in which experts were incorporated into city politics. This book demonstrates the significance of expertise as a potential source of change in American politics and policy, and of each city's electoral and administrative organizations as mediating institutions within a national system of urban political economies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aAggregate approach to reform.  aBryan, Williams Jennings.  aCermak, Anton.  aCity-manager government.  aCooley Farms colony.  aDaley, Richard J.  aEmerson, Haven.  aHaider, Donald.  aHeritage Foundation.  aIndependence League.  aIndustrial social scientists.  aKaufman, Herbert.  aLarson, Magali Sarfatti.  aMcKinley, William.  aMorgan, J. P.  aNew York Central Railroad.  aPolicy planning networks.  aRAND Corporation.  aShefter, Martin.  aSocial hygiene experts.  aSocial scientists.  aSteffens, Lincoln.  aUrban liberalism.  aVoinovich, George.  aWashington, Harold.  aYellowitz, Irwin.  aYerkes, Charles.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691221632zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691221632423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691221632.jpg  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999c1927d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_E